<DOC><DOCNO> AP880421-0291 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-04-21-88 1343EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f BC-Earns-Brokers     04-21 0188</FIRST><SECOND>BC-Earns-Brokers,0200</SECOND><HEAD>Salomon Reports Higher Quarterly Earnings</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Salomon Inc. reported Thursday its first quarterprofit rose 16 percent over a year ago, reflecting strength in thecompany's securities and commodities units.   The giant financial services company said it netted $173million, or $1.19 a share, during the first three months of thisyear, compared with $149 million, or $1.13 a share, in the sameperiod of 987.   Quarterly revenue, however, fell to $1.61 billion from $1.72billion.   Pre-tax earnings at the company's Salomon Brothers brokerageunit rose to $253 million from $248 million in 1987, which``reverses a nine-month period of declining profitability,''Chairman John Gutfreund said.   In Salomon's commodities operations, Phibro Energy's earningsbefore taxes totaled $27 million, up from $24 million.   Salomon's Philipp Brothers unit reported its pre-tax profit wasup five-fold, to $15 million from $3 million. Salomon CommercialFinance earned $45 million, compared with $36 million.   ``After a difficult restructuring period and the streamlining ofthe securities organization last fall, and post-crash turmoil infinancial markets, our expectations of improved profitability arebeing realized,'' Gutfreund said in a statement.</TEXT></DOC>